Processing of data comparing MagReSyn and SP3

Description

This file contains the code for processing the search and quantification output files from the examination of the performance of SP3 in comparison to MagReSyn. These data were used to make portions of Figure XXXXX.

  • MGF files were generated using RawQuant.
  • The data were searched using SearchCLI and PeptideShakerCLI.
  • Raw files were parsed for quantification data with RawQuant.

Analysis

First thing we want to do is compile the identifications data into a usable object for plotting. This involves taking the output from PeptideShaker and combining it with the RawQuant data. This is carried out using the code below.

First I will compile the identification data.

id_files = list.files('/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/projects-current/sp3-follow-up/magresyn-testing/reports-output', pattern='.*Default_PSM_Report.txt',full.names=TRUE) #psm files 
quant_files = list.files('/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/projects-current/sp3-follow-up/magresyn-testing/quant-output', pattern='.*QuantData.txt',full.names=TRUE) #ms2 quant files

Read in the identification data into a single data frame object.

id_parsed = data.frame() #identification data storage object
#iterate over the identification files 
for (i in 1:length(id_files)){
  psm_in = read.table(id_files[i],header=TRUE,sep='\t') #input file
  psm_f1 = psm_in %>% 
    dplyr::select(Protein.s., Sequence, Spectrum.File, Spectrum.Title, m.z, Identification.Charge) %>% #select columns
    dplyr::mutate(Spectrum.Title, scan_num = sub(".*?spectrum (.*?)", "\\1", Spectrum.Title)) %>% #parse out the scan number
    dplyr::mutate(Identification.Charge, id_charge = gsub("[^0-9]", "", Identification.Charge)) %>% #parse out the charge
    dplyr::mutate(Spectrum.Title, fraction = sub(".*?hph_(.*?)_MGF\\.mgf", "\\1", Spectrum.File)) %>% #parse the fraction
    dplyr::select(Protein.s., Sequence, scan_num, m.z, id_charge, fraction) %>% #select new columns
    dplyr::mutate(Protein.s., first_accession = sapply(strsplit(as.character(Protein.s.),"\\,"), `[`, 1)) #parse the accession
  #adjust the column names
  colnames(psm_f1) = c('accession_groups','sequence','ScanNumber','id_precursor_mz','id_charge','fraction','accession')
  psm_f2 = dplyr::filter(psm_f1, !grepl('CONT_', accession_groups)) #remove the contaminant proteins
  id_parsed = rbind(id_parsed,psm_f2) #group the data with the previously processed set
}

Now we can process the rawquant data for the TMT values.

quant_parsed = data.frame()
#iterate over the rawquant files
for (i in 1:length(quant_files)){
  quant_in = read.table(quant_files[i],header=TRUE,sep='\t') #grab the input file
  #change values that are zero to NA
  quant_in[,15:50][quant_in[,15:50] == 0] = NA
  #rearrange the data frame
  quant_meta = quant_in[,c('PrecursorMass','ScanNumber','MS1ScanNumber','RetentionTime',
                           'PrecursorCharge','MS2IonInjectionTime','MS1Interference',
                           'tmt126_mass','tmt127N_mass','tmt128C_mass','tmt129N_mass','tmt130C_mass',
                           'tmt131_mass')]
  quant_exprs = quant_in[,c('tmt126_intensity','tmt127N_intensity','tmt128C_intensity',
                            'tmt129N_intensity','tmt130C_intensity','tmt131_intensity',
                            'tmt126_noise','tmt127N_noise','tmt128C_noise','tmt129N_noise','tmt130C_noise',
                            'tmt131_noise')]
  #calculate signal to noise
  quant_sn = quant_exprs[,c(1:6)] / quant_exprs[,c(7:12)] #signal-to-noise calculation
  quant_sn$totalIntensity = rowSums(quant_exprs[,1:6],na.rm=TRUE) #total intensity calculation
  quant_sn$totalSN = rowSums(quant_sn[,1:6],na.rm=TRUE) #total signal-to-noise calculation
  quant_sn$totalNoise = rowSums(quant_exprs[,7:12],na.rm=TRUE) #total noise calculation
  quant_sn$totalNA = rowSums(is.na(quant_sn[,1:6])) #information about missing values
  quant_meta$fraction = sub(".*?hph_(.*?)_Q.*", "\\1", quant_files[i]) #add the fraction column
  quant_matrix = cbind(quant_meta,quant_sn) #bind the information and quantification together
  quant_parsed = rbind(quant_parsed, quant_matrix) #bind into a single frame
}

Now we can combine the two data sets together using a simple merge and save the data.

So this appears to be significant. Now I want to look at identification overlap. For this I am going to filter the data based on a few criteria:

  • the summed signal to noise across all channels must be greater than 100
  • the number of NA values must be 3 or less
  • signal values below a signal to noise of 10 will be set to zero
##go back to the psm level data to filter
psm_filter1 = subset(psm_set, totalSN >= 100) #filter by signal to noise
psm_filter2 = subset(psm_filter1, totalNA <= 3) #filter by NA values
psm_filter2[, 20:25][psm_filter2[, 20:25] < 10] = NA #filter by signal to noise of individual channels
  
###now compile to peptides
psm_agg <- setDT(psm_filter2)[, lapply(.SD,sum,na.rm=TRUE),by=.(sequence),.SDcols=c('tmt126_intensity','tmt127N_intensity','tmt128C_intensity',

setDF(psm_agg) # convert back to dataframe

Now, if we want to calculate peptides identified by only one method, we need to assign a threshold. Let’s say that a peptide has to reach a signal to noise above 30 and have just 1 NA value across the 3 replicate channels in order to be considered identifed.

###need to convert values less than 10 to NA again, it gets reset
psm_agg[, 2:7][psm_agg[, 2:7] < 10] = NA #convert to NA values
psm_agg$sp3_signal = rowSums(psm_agg[,c(2:4)], na.rm=TRUE) #sum the SP3 signal

Now we can perform the differential expression analysis with limma.

#calculate differential expression using limma
eset = as.matrix(log2(pro_set[,c(3:8)])) #log transform the expression data and transfer to a new object
design <- cbind(SP3=c(1,1,1,0,0,0),MAG=c(0,0,0,1,1,1)) #create the design matrix
fit <- lmFit(eset,design) #calculate the linear model of the expression values
Partial NA coefficients for 1 probe(s)
cont.matrix <- makeContrasts(SP3vsMAG=SP3-MAG, levels=design) #create the contrasts matrix
fit2 <- contrasts.fit(fit, cont.matrix) #calculate the contrasts
fit2 <- eBayes(fit2) #empirical Bayes smoothing
logFC = fit2$coef #extract fold changes
pVal = fit2$p.value #extract p-values
p.adj = p.adjust(fit2$p.value, method="BH") #apply multiple testing correction to the p-values
#insert the data back into the original matrix
pro_set$logFC <- logFC
pro_set$p.value <- pVal
pro_set$p.adj.value <- p.adj
pro_ordered = pro_set[order(-pro_set$logFC),] #reorder the matrix by fold change
write.table(pro_ordered, '/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/projects-current/sp3-follow-up/magresyn-testing/Routput/ch_feb2018_SP3-magresyn_id-quant-proteins.txt', sep = '\t', row.names = FALSE, col.names = TRUE, quote = FALSE)

Now we can plot the differential expression, for visualization purposes.

What about other protein properties, like size, hydrophobicity?

###for this we need the protein sequences. We can use our original database for this.
humanDB = readAAStringSet('/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/databases/feb2018/uniprot_human-crap-feb2018_FWD.fasta')
#extract out the SP3 data of interest
sp3_data = data.frame()
for (i in 1:nrow(sp3_enriched)){
  accession_query = sp3_enriched$accession[i] #get the uniprot id
  accession_location = which(grepl(accession_query,names(humanDB))) #get the location of that sequence
  accession_length = nchar(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location]))) #get the length of the protein
  accession_mw = mw(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location]))) #get the mw of the protein
  accession_hydrophobicity = hydrophobicity(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location])), scale='KyteDoolittle') #get the hydrophobicity
  #accession_type = membpos(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location]))) #get the type
  sp3_data[i,1] = accession_query #output
  sp3_data[i,2] = accession_length #output
  sp3_data[i,3] = accession_mw #output
  sp3_data[i,4] = accession_hydrophobicity #output
  #sp3_data[i,5] = accession_type #output
  colnames(sp3_data) = c('name','length','mw','hydro') #annotation
}
#extract out the MAG data of interest
mag_data = data.frame()
for (i in 1:nrow(mag_enriched)){
  accession_query = mag_enriched$accession[i] #get the uniprot id
  accession_location = which(grepl(accession_query,names(humanDB))) #get the location of that sequence
  accession_length = nchar(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location]))) #get the length of the protein
  accession_mw = mw(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location]))) #get the mw of the protein
  accession_hydrophobicity = hydrophobicity(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location])), scale='KyteDoolittle') #get the hydrophobicity
  #accession_type = membpos(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location]))) #get the type
  mag_data[i,1] = accession_query #output
  mag_data[i,2] = accession_length #output
  mag_data[i,3] = accession_mw #output
  mag_data[i,4] = accession_hydrophobicity #output
  #mag_data[i,5] = accession_type #output
  colnames(mag_data) = c('name','length','mw','hydro') #annotation
}

#extract out the SP3 data of interest
sp3_comp = data.frame(empty_column=0) #make a dummy data frame
for (i in 1:nrow(sp3_enriched)){
  accession_query = sp3_enriched$accession[i] #get the uniprot id
  accession_location = which(grepl(accession_query,names(humanDB))) #get the location of that sequence
  accession_comp = as.data.frame(aaComp(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location])))) #get the composition
  sp3_comp = cbind(sp3_comp, accession_comp[,1])
  row.names(sp3_comp) = row.names(accession_comp)
}
#extract out the MAG data of interest
mag_comp = data.frame(empty_column=0) #make a dummy data frame
for (i in 1:nrow(mag_enriched)){
  accession_query = mag_enriched$accession[i] #get the uniprot id
  accession_location = which(grepl(accession_query,names(humanDB))) #get the location of that sequence
  accession_comp = as.data.frame(aaComp(as.character(unlist(humanDB[accession_location])))) #get the composition
  mag_comp = cbind(mag_comp, accession_comp[,1])
  row.names(mag_comp) = row.names(accession_comp)
}
###now process the data to totals
sp3_totals = rowSums(sp3_comp[,2:70],na.rm=TRUE) #sp3 totals
mag_totals = rowSums(mag_comp[,2:113],na.rm=TRUE) #mag totals
#normalize the totals to percent
sp3_percents = (sp3_totals / sum(sp3_totals)) *100
mag_percents = (mag_totals / sum(mag_totals)) *100
#now prepare the data to plot
sp3_melted = melt(sp3_percents) #melt the data
sp3_melted$dataset = 'sp3' #add dataset identifier
mag_melted = melt(mag_percents) #melt the data
mag_melted$dataset = 'mag' #add dataset identifier
sp3_mag_comp = rbind(sp3_melted,mag_melted) #bind the data
sp3_mag_comp$type = rep(row.names(sp3_mag_comp)[1:9],2) #get identifiers

Now plot the composition data.

comp_barplot = ggplot(sp3_mag_comp, aes(type, value, fill = dataset)) +
  geom_col(width=0.75, position = position_dodge(width=0.75), alpha = 0.25) +

  labs(x = "type", y = 'percent', title = 'sp3 protein composition') +
  scale_fill_manual(values=brewer.pal(6,"RdBu")[c(1,6)]) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,20), breaks = seq(0,20,5)) +
